title: For Sale:  1911A1 Argentine Navy
postcontent: For sale is what I believe to be an Argentine Navy 1911A1 that has never been issued. In my 30 plus years of collecting firearms I believe I have acquired enough knowledge and expertise to know when a firearm because of condition has not been subjected to the wear of normal use.  Argentine 1911A1's were made on the same machinery as Colt 1911A1's and were made of the finest British, Swedish and German steel.  I have never seen a 1911A1 with a barrel as shiny on the inside as this one.  All numbers match except the magazine which is only 5 digits difference.  All systemas were originally finished in black oxide,except a few that were specially ordered for the Navy.  Many were later re-finished, most Navy pistols in parkerization. Only 6,226 Systemas were made for the Argentine Navy.    More information can be read on the 1911 Forum when you do a search on the Argentine 1911A1's. This pistol was manufactured in 1958 and is in great shape, see the pictures.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt Government 1911 - Custom Shop - special Edition made for U.S. Customs
postcontent:
Here it is ... A special Collector item: A Colt Government 1911 (.45ACP) -- Special Custom Shop made to commemorate 200 years of U. S. Customs Existence.

Made in 1989 -- only 400 pieces made. The story behind it is the following: The US Treasury ordered 400 pieces of this out of which gave 350 to special US Customs agents. The other fifty they sold it ONLY to other US Customs agents who wanted to buy it as collector items. I know that because I bought it from the original owner, who was a US Customs agent (I saw his ID), now retired. This is #363 out of 400. He bought 4 of them back in 1989. It has gold roll marks on both sides, and a pair of grips that has the golden shield of the Department of the Treasury (back then US Customs were not part of the Homeland Security which was created after 9/11). If you are willing to pay $100 Colt will tell you in a historic letter the same things I am telling you for free. I know all of these because the guy who sold it to me showed me a letter from Colt (and I will try to make a copy of his letter and include it with everything else -- the letter is for a different gun #).

Now, this pistol is in MINT condition. It has never been fired. Just lubed, drooled over from time to time :-)

It comes with an authentic US Customs patch (which was added by the previous owner), an authentic US Customs shield (still in the wrap) that has the same number as the gun, a US Customs sticker, all in a beautiful mahogany presentation box with a key. Also includes the original paper box with the Styrofoam insert and the paper box. I will take more detailed pictures and post them later ...

$3,500 ... I take US Postal Money Orders, or a personal check. I will ship this to your FFL (FedEX overnight) for $50 extra, if you are in a different state other than WA or if you are in Eastern WA. If you send me a personal check, please expect me to send it out 10 days after I deposit the check in my account. Also, if you send me a personal check I want to see a copy of your ID and CHL. I am in Centralia and many times I travel down to Portland-Vancouver area.

postcontent: Here is a Replica of the civilian version of the FN P90 the PS90. It has a Well p90 stock that has been gutted and the shell alone used, bedded to accept the the 597 receiver and barrel which is completely stock. Cutouts have been made in the stock for the charging handle and ejection of spent cases as well as for the magazine release and cutout on the bottom for a magazine well to accept either the included factory 10 round magazine or either of the 30 round remington magazines that are included 1 clear and 1 black.  There is two safeties the one on the trigger as well as a access door on the butt of the stock that you can open that allows you to engage the 597's cross bolt safety. It was made using a 20" barrel to make the firearms overall length meet the federal guidelines 26" minimum OVERALL rimfire rifle length there by also surpassing the guideline for 16" minimum rimfire barrel length. I have built several .22 conversions this was my first one I did based on seeing many other internet forums where people did this with the 10/22 I just happen to prefer my 597s and model 60's a little more so thought I would give it a go. It shoots great runs as should be expected with minimal jams ftf fte than a 597 would in a regular stock out of roughly 3-400 rounds that have been fired in this rifle maybe 3 or 4 failures and I attribute that to the 30 rd mags as they tend to hiccup in all my 597's every once in awhile. There is no optic included so you would need to supply your own reflex sight red dot scope what ever you prefer. This was a brand new rifle that was bought to put into this stock I also have a original stock that can go with it if you would like. The clear 30rd mag has been used the black one is new. This is a very fun unique well functioning firearm that is a very close replica to the real FN p90 dimensions weight firing characteristics all similar yet fires the much less expensive .22lr in the same manner a m&p 15-22 would be to a .223 m&p ar. Will entertain cash offers not sure what to ask have several hours of assembly as well as cost of rifle mags stock etc... would really like to do some trading so make some fair offers. Thanks for looking!!!
